content:
Psy


Park Jae-sang (Korean: 박재상; Hanja: 朴載相, IPA: [pɐk̚.t͡ɕεsɐŋ]; born December 31, 1977), known professionally as Psy (싸이; /saɪ/ SY; Korean: [s͈ai]), stylized in all caps, is a South Korean singer, rapper, songwriter, and record producer. Psy is known domestically for his humorous videos and stage performances, and internationally for his hit single "Gangnam Style". The song's refrain was entered into The Yale Book of Quotations as one of the most famous quotations of 2012.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.nbcmiami.com/news/local/2012-Top-Quotes-From-Binders-Full-of-Women-to-Gangnam-Style-182734061.html", "title": "2012 Top Quotes: From 'Binders Full of Women' to 'Gangnam Style'", "publisher": "NBC Miami (Associated Press)"}
On October 23, 2012, Psy met United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon at the UN Headquarters where Ban expressed his desire to work with the singer because of his "unlimited global reach".{"citetype": "news", "title": "Rapper Psy brings Gangnam Style horseplay to United Nations", "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/oct/24/psy-gangnam-style-united-nations", "work": "The Guardian", "location": "London", "accessdate": "October 24, 2012", "last": "Davies", "first": "Lizzy"} On December 21, 2012, his music video for "Gangnam Style" exceeded one billion views on YouTube, becoming the first video to do so in the website's history.{"citetype": "news", "url": "http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/12/21/psy-gangnam-style-billion-views-youtube/", "title ": "PSY Gangnam Style Billion Views Youtube", "work ": "Entertainment Weekly"}{"citetype": "news", "url": "http://news.cnet.com/8301-1023_3-57560498-93/gangnam-style-becomes-first-video-to-hit-1-billion-youtube-views/", "title ": "'Gangnam Style' becomes first video to hit 1 billion", "publisher ": "CNET"} Psy was subsequently recognized by the media as the "King of YouTube".{"citetype": "news", "title": "Psy now king of YouTube", "url": "http://www.news.com.au/news/psy-becomes-youtube-no1/story-fnejlvvj-1226523695116", "publisher": "News.com.au", "accessdate": "December 2, 2012"}{"citetype": "news", "title": "Move over Bieber \u2013 Gangnam is new YouTube king", "url": "http://edition.cnn.com/2012/11/24/showbiz/gangnam-style/index.html", "publisher": "CNN", "accessdate": "December 2, 2012", "last": "Ariosto", "first": "David"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/move-over-bieber-psy-s-the-new-king-of-youtube-1.1052882", "title": "Move over Bieber, PSY's the new king of YouTube", "publisher": "CTV Television Network"} On May 31, 2014, the video for Psy's Gangnam Style hit two billion views. As of December 2019[update], it is the seventh most viewed video on YouTube, with over 3.4 billion views.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9bZkp7q19f0", "title": "PSY - GANGNAM STYLE(\uac15\ub0a8\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc77c) M/V", "website": "Youtube", "publisher": "Psy"}
In December 2012, MTV noted Psy's rise from being little known outside South Korea, to being hailed as the "Viral Star of 2012".{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1699080/psy-gangnam-style-viral-sensation-2012.jhtml", "title": "Psy's 'Gangnam Style' Is Our Viral Sensation of the Year", "last": "Kaufman", "first": "Gil", "publisher": "MTV"} On December 31, 2012, Psy performed in a globally televised New Year's Eve celebration with American rapper MC Hammer on-stage in front of a live audience of over a million people in Times Square, New York City.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.ibtimes.com/new-years-eve-2013-times-square-photos-psys-gangnam-style-ryan-seacrest-thousands-colorful-new", "title": "New Year's Eve 2013 Times Square Photos: Psy's 'Gangnam Style,' Ryan Seacrest And Thousands Of Colorful New Yorkers", "date": "January 1, 2013", "work": "The International Business Times", "author": "Kukil Bora"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "January 1, 2013", "title": "Taylor Swift, Psy, Mayor Bloomberg help New Yorkers ring in 2013", "url": "http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/new-year-eve-celebrations-underway-new-york-article-1.1230729", "work": "Daily News", "location": "New York", "author1": "Kerry Burke", "author2": "Jennifer H. Cunningham", "author3": "Daniel Beekman"}

Early life
Park Jae-sang was born on December 31, 1977,{"citetype": "book", "date": "April 29, 2014", "title": "K-Pop Now!: The Korean Music Revolution", "url": "https://books.google.com/books?id=etDZAwAAQBAJ", "publisher": "Tuttle Publishing", "page": "106", "author": "Mark Russell"} to an affluent family in the Gangnam District of Seoul, South Korea.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://video.today.msnbc.msn.com/today/49192707#49192707", "title": "PSY goes home, gets 'Gangnam-Style' welcom", "date": "September 27, 2012", "publisher": "MSNBC", "accessdate": "September 29, 2012", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20120930050755/http://video.today.msnbc.msn.com/today/49192707#49192707", "archivedate": "September 30, 2012"} His father, Park Won-Ho, is the executive chairman of DI Corporation, a manufacturer of semiconductor manufacturing equipment listed on the Korea Exchange.{"citetype": "news", "title": "&quot;Gangnam Style&quot; hit doubles value of Psy's father's stock", "url": "https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/25/entertainment-us-korea-psy-stock-idUSBRE88O03Z20120925", "agency": "Reuters", "accessdate": "October 26, 2012"} His mother, Kim Young-hee, owns several restaurants in Gangnam.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.travelweekly.com/Asia-Travel/Seoul-music-K-pop-in-Korea-capital/", "title": "Seoul music: K-pop in Korea's capital", "last": "Harris", "first": "Mark Edward", "accessdate": "February 12, 2013", "work": "[[Travel Weekly]]"}
Park attended Banpo (반포) Elementary and Middle Schools and Sehwa (세화) High School.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=\uc2f8\uc774&os=158367", "title": "Psy Profile", "publisher": "naver"} He disliked school and was known as the class clown. In an interview on South Korea's Seoul Broadcasting System, a former teacher of Park said: "I remember Psy making a lot of sexual jokes during class. He had such a big influence that he would drive the entire class to his jokes. I disliked him at the time, but looking back, I see that he added a great energy to the class."{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.soompi.com/2012/10/12/psys-yearbook-photo-and-mischievous-childhood-revealed/", "title": "PSY's Yearbook Photo and Mischievous Childhood Revealed!", "publisher": "Soompi"}
Park told CNN's Alina Cho that when he was 15 years old, he watched a Korean TV programme that introduced foreign pop music. One particular episode showed a concert at Wembley Stadium held by the British rock band Queen where they performed their 1975 hit single "Bohemian Rhapsody". Park said it was this concert footage that sparked his love for music.{"citetype": "news", "title": "Psy: Growing up 'Gangnam Style'", "url": "http://edition.cnn.com/video/#/video/world/2012/11/23/exp-talk-asia-psy-growing-gangnam.cnn", "publisher": "CNN"}

1996–2000: Brief study in the United States and career beginnings
As part of preparations to take over DI Corporation from his father, Park had originally planned to study business administration at Boston University in 1996.{"citetype": "news", "title": "Psy vows topless show if 'Gangnam Style' hits No. 1", "url": "http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-09-25/news/34086640_1_psy-fame-dance", "work": "Daily News", "location": "New York"} However, upon his arrival in the United States, he lost interest in his studies,{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.korea.net/NewsFocus/Culture/view?articleId=102999", "title": "PSY, the man behind the name", "last": "Tack-Whan", "first": "Wi", "publisher": "Korea.net"} spending his remaining tuition funds on musical instruments and entertainment equipment, including a computer, an electric keyboard, and a MIDI interface.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/10/28/psy-talks-gangnam-style-growing-up-and-his-next-single.html", "title": "Psy Talks Gangnam Style, Growing Up, and His Next Single", "last": "Stern", "first": "Marlow", "work": "Daily Beast"} After attending an English-language summer course and studying for one semester, Park dropped out of Boston University and applied to study at Berklee College of Music instead. During his time at Berklee, Park took core curriculum lessons in ear training, contemporary writing and music synthesis, but he soon dropped out and returned to South Korea to pursue a career as a singer, without having attained a degree from either Boston University or Berklee.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.ellentv.com/2012/09/19/did-you-know-this-about-psy/", "title": "Did You Know This About Psy?", "publisher": "Ellen TV", "accessdate": "October 28, 2012", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://www.webcitation.org/6DczWUv30?url=http://www.ellentv.com/2012/09/19/did-you-know-this-about-psy/"}{"citetype": "news", "title": "BU hopes to get donation from former student Psy, the South Korean rapper known for 'Gangnam Style' hit", "url": "http://www.boston.com/yourtown/news/allston_brighton/2012/10/bu_hopes_to_get_donation_from.html", "work": "Boston Globe", "accessdate": "October 26, 2012", "last": "Rocheleau", "first": "Matt"}{"citetype": "news", "title": "BU hopes to get donation from former student Psy, the South Korean rapper known for 'Gangnam Style' hit", "url": "http://www.boston.com/yourtown/news/allston_brighton/2012/10/bu_hopes_to_get_donation_from.html?camp", "work": "Boston Globe", "accessdate": "October 28, 2012", "last": "Brighton", "first": "Allston"}
In South Korea, Psy made his first appearance on Korean national television in 2000 after his dancing caught the eye of a TV producer.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/yourtown/oxford/10033043.Gangnam_Style_a_hit_with_Oxford_students/", "title": "Gangnam Style a hit with Oxford students", "last": "Harrison", "first": "Emma", "work": "The Oxford Times"}

2001–02: Psy from the Psycho World!, controversy, and domestic success
In January 2001, Psy debuted his full-length album Psy from the Psycho World!, for which he was fined by South Korean government authorities due to his album's "inappropriate content".{"citetype": "news", "title": "Gangnam Rile: Psy's Past Anti-American Performances Stir Controversy", "url": "http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/12/08/gangnam-rile-psys-past-anti-american-performances-stir-controversy/", "work": "Time", "accessdate": "December 19, 2012", "last": "Carbone", "first": "Nick"} Psy was a rookie hip hop singer that stirred up the Korean pop music scene with very blunt lyrics, peculiar dance moves and an unconventional appearance that earned him the nickname "The Bizarre Singer".{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://rki.kbs.co.kr/english/program/program_artist_detail.htm?No=10071", "title": "KBS WORLD - Psy Biography", "publisher": "[[KBS World Radio]]"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1693607/britney-spears-psy-gangnam-style.jhtml", "title": "Britney Spears Learns Psy's 'Gangnam Style' On Ellen Britney's wish is Ellen DeGeneres' command, as 'X Factor' judge meets Psy after tweeting about his dance.", "last": "Garibaldi", "first": "Christina", "publisher": "MTV"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.people.com/people/package/article/0,,20302940_20627446,00.html", "title": "PSY: 5 Things to Know About the 'Gangnam Style' Rapper", "last": "Coughlan", "first": "Maggie", "publisher": "[[People (magazine)|People]]"}
His second album Sa 2 also created controversy upon its release in 2002, earning complaints from civil groups due to the potentially negative influence his album would have on children and teenagers. Since then, Psy has been thought of as a controversial artist, and Sa 2 was banned in 2002 from being sold to the under-19 set. In September of the same year, Psy released his third album 3 Psy. The album's title song, "Champion", saw great success partly due to the hype from the World Cup games held in Seoul. Despite the significant amount of controversy surrounding his music, Psy was awarded songwriting accolades at the annual Seoul Music Awards, marking his breakthrough in the South Korean music industry.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.mtv.com/artists/psy/biography/", "title": "About Psy", "publisher": "MTV"}

2003–09: Military service, Ssajib, and re-enlistment
In 2003, Psy was conscripted into the South Korean military as part of mandatory military service imposed on all South Korean men aged 18 to 35.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://sg.entertainment.yahoo.com/news/psy-thank-fans-free-gangnam-style-concert-044608559.html", "title": "Psy brings 'Gangnam Style' home with free show", "last": "Hewitt", "first": "Giles", "publisher": "Yahoo!"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://rki.kbs.co.kr/english/program/program_artist_detail.htm?No=10071", "title": "Artist search: Psy", "publisher": "KBS"} Psy was excused from military duty due to working at a software development company (the South Korean government grants exemptions to those with technical expertise work in companies that serve the national interest). He was expected to be released from duties in 2005.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/04/117_4583.html", "title": "'Psy May Be Enlisted for Military Service Again", "accessdate": "October 27, 2012", "work": "The Korea Times"} In 2006, Psy released his fourth album Ssajib, which won honors at the 2006 SBS Music Awards and Hong Kong's Mnet Asian Music Awards.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.mtv.com/artists/psy/biography/", "title": "About Psy", "publisher": "MTV"}
In 2007, state prosecutors accused Psy of "neglecting" his work, holding concerts and appearing on local television networks during his period of prior employment.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/04/117_15438.html", "title": "Psy Called Up for Military Again", "accessdate": "October 27, 2012", "work": "The Korea Times"} On October 12, 2007, the Seoul Administrative Court decided that Psy must be redrafted, rejecting a lawsuit filed by Psy against the Military Manpower Administration (MMA) in August. Two months later, Psy was re-drafted into the military where he had held the rank of Private First Class and served as a signalman in the 52nd Army Infantry Division, before being released from duties in July 2009.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JVKTm7MdtfE", "title": "Singer Psy during his 2008 stint in the military", "last": "AFP", "publisher": "YouTube (AFP)"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/04/117_15438.html", "title": "Singer Psy to Be Redrafted", "last": "Park", "first": "Si-soo", "work": "The Korea Times"}

2010–12: 5th studio album and debut performance in Japan
Owing to financial difficulties, Psy could no longer release his own songs. His wife encouraged him to join the South Korean music label YG Entertainment, whose founder and chief executive officer Yang Hyun-suk was an old friend of Psy's.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/12239/20120809/psy-tablo-wives-thank-yg-entertainment-yang-hyun-suk-k-pop.htm", "title": "YG Entertainment, &quot;It's all Thanks to the Wives of Psy and Tablo", "date": "August 9, 2012", "accessdate": "September 4, 2012"} In 2010, Psy joined YG Entertainment.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.dkpopnews.net/2010/10/news-psy-reveals-reason-why-he-joined.html", "title": "Psy reveals the reason why he joined YG Entertainment", "publisher": "dkpopnews.net"} The K-pop singer Kim Hee-chul, from the boyband Super Junior, expressed that he had wished Psy would have joined his group's label SM Entertainment instead.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.allkpop.com/2010/11/kim-heechul-regrets-psy-joining-yg-entertainment", "title": "Kim Heechul regrets Psy joining YG Entertainment", "publisher": "Allkpop"} Psy released his fifth album PsyFive in 2010, and its lead single "Right Now" was banned from under-19 audiences by South Korea's Ministry of Gender Equality and Family for what it deemed an "obscene" lyric, "Life is like toxic alcohol".{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.allkpop.com/2011/09/psys-right-now-gets-banned-by-the-ministry-of-gender-equality-and-family", "title": "Psy's &quot;Right Now&quot; gets banned by the Ministry of Gender Equality and Family", "publisher": "Allkpop"} Despite the ban, Psy received awards during the 2011 Melon Music Awards and Mnet Asian Music Awards.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.mtv.com/artists/psy/biography/", "title": "About Psy", "publisher": "MTV"} Psy had, up until this point, topped domestic music charts half a dozen times throughout his twelve-year career in South Korea.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/474456/psys-gangnam-style-the-billboard-cover-story", "title": "PSY's 'Gangnam Style': The Billboard Cover Story", "last": "Kwak", "first": "Donnie", "work": "Billboard"}
On January 7, 2012, Psy performed alongside K-pop bands Bigbang and 2NE1 in front of 80,000 Japanese fans during the YG Family Concert in Osaka. His performance was broadcast by Mezamashi TV (mezamashi meaning "wake-up alarm"), a Japanese news magazine show produced by Fuji Television. This marked his first appearance on a foreign broadcasting network.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.soompi.com/2012/01/10/psy-catches-the-attention-of-japanese-media/", "title": "PSY Catches the Attention of Japanese Media", "publisher": "Soompi"} During the concert, Psy introduced himself to his Japanese fans with a sign that read "I'm a famous singer well known for driving the audience wild in Korea, but here, today, I'm just a little chubby newcomer" and sang five of his hit songs while Japanese TV commentators expressed their approval in their astonishment at his humorous incorporation of the moves of Lady Gaga and Beyoncé.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://global.mnet.com/news/newsdetail.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201201101007_2669", "title": "Psy Wows Japanese Music Fans", "last": "Ji Yeon", "first": "Kim", "publisher": "Mnet Media"}

2012–13: "Gangnam Style" and unexpected international breakthrough
In July 2012, Psy released his sixth album Psy 6 (Six Rules), Part 1 and the song "Gangnam Style" appeared in broadcasting networks and newspapers outside Asia.{"citetype": "news", "date": "August 27, 2012", "title": "Wild, Crazy Style", "last": "Fekadu", "first": "Mesfin", "newspaper": "Daily Express"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.iltasanomat.fi/musiikki/art-1288486980607.html", "title": "Unohtakaa Macarena, t\u00e4ss\u00e4 tulee hevostanssi!", "date": "July 28, 2012", "language": "fi", "transtitle": "Forget about Macarena, here comes the horse dance!", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://www.webcitation.org/6CTIwbf8p?url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/musiikki/art-1288486980607.html", "work": "Ilta-Sanomat"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "August 2, 2012", "title": "Gangnam Style goes viral in rap video", "publisher": "CNN"} On August 14, "Gangnam Style" ranked first on YouTube's 'Most Viewed Videos' monthly chart;{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.allkpop.com/2012/08/psys-gangnam-style-ranks-1-on-youtubes-monthly-chart", "title": "Psy's &quot;Gangnam Style&quot; ranks No. 1 on YouTube's monthly chart", "date": "August 13, 2012", "accessdate": "September 4, 2012"} on August 21, 2012, "Gangnam Style" officially charted No. 1 on the iTunes Music Video Charts, overtaking Justin Bieber's "As Long as You Love Me" and Katy Perry's "Wide Awake"; this feat was the first for a South Korean artist. After the video went viral, celebrities quickly jumped on board, with Katy Perry, Britney Spears, and Tom Cruise taking to Twitter to share their delight.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.4music.com/artists/223/Psy", "title": "The world's first global Korean pop star", "publisher": "4Music.com", "accessdate": "November 8, 2012", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20121114053402/http://www.4music.com/artists/223/Psy"} The Gangnam Style phenomenon has also popularized his older music videos, such as "Right Now".{"citetype": "news", "date": "August 21, 2012", "title": "Baseball Goes Gangnam Style", "url": "https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2012/08/21/baseball-goes-gangnam-style/", "publisher": "Wall Street Journal \u2013 Korea Real Time", "author": "Jaeyeon Woo"} On September 14, 2012, he appeared on The Today Show on NBC in New York City, performing the song live and teaching dance moves to the anchors.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://toyotaconcertseries.today.com/_news/2012/09/14/13860081-today-goes-gangnam-style-with-psy", "title": "TODAY goes Gangnam style with PSY! \u2013 Toyota Concert Series", "publisher": "Toyotaconcertseries.today.com"} The following day, he also made a cameo appearance on Saturday Night Live during a skit featuring "Gangnam Style".{"citetype": "news", "title": "Psy brings 'Gangnam Style' to 'SNL'", "url": "https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/2012/09/16/gangnam-style-on-snl/1574701/", "work": "USA TODAY", "accessdate": "April 27, 2018"} Commenting on his popularity among foreign celebrities, Psy said:
When I realized that some top stars like have imagined or tweeted about me, I thought, "That's joking. That's not gonna happen" ... I never expect things like this, not because they are top stars, but because this is the biggest market in the universe for pop music, right, so everybody's dreaming about having appearance in the U.S. so I’m still saying, "What going on here? This is beautiful."{"citetype": "news", "title": "Korean rapper PSY goes viral with music video", "url": "http://thechronicleherald.ca/artslife/129694-korean-rapper-psy-goes-viral-with-music-video", "accessdate": "September 1, 2012", "last": "Fekadu", "first": "Mesfin", "newspaper": "Chronicle Herald"}Riding high on the success of "Gangnam Style", Psy was signed by Scooter Braun to Braun's Schoolboy Records, a label distributed by Republic Records.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/475306/psy-signs-to-scooter-brauns-label-will-appear-at-mtv-vmas", "title": "Psy Signs to Scooter Braun's Label, Will Appear at MTV VMAs", "work": "Billboard"} In early September, the Gangnam district awarded Psy with a plaque and named him an honorary ambassador.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.google.com/hostednews/getty/article/ALeqM5hW1g-qiDntiwAqi3hy5QoAllRF_w?docId=152709979", "title": "Getty Images: Inside Seoul's Gangnam District"} On October 24, 2012, Psy was recognized by the United Nations as an "International sensation".{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=43373&Cr=secretary-general&Cr1=#.UIkp12fAHLQ", "title": "From Korean pop music to skydiving to Earth \u2013 not-your-typical diplomatic meetings for UN Secretary-General", "publisher": "United Nations"} According to Reuters, U.N. Secretary General Ban Ki-moon scheduled a meeting with Psy in the belief that music has great power to overcome intolerance.{"citetype": "news", "title": "U.N. chief to meet South Korean pop star, Austrian skydiver", "url": "https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/10/23/entertainment-us-un-gangnam-skydive-idUSBRE89M12L20121023", "agency": "Reuters", "accessdate": "October 23, 2012", "first": "Michelle", "last": "Nichols"} On October 23, 2012, they met at the United Nations Headquarters where Ban expressed his desire to work with Psy. He remarked that Psy has an "unlimited global reach" and said, "I hope that we can work together using your global reach".{"citetype": "news", "title": "Rapper Psy brings Gangnam Style horseplay to United Nations", "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/oct/24/psy-gangnam-style-united-nations", "work": "The Guardian", "location": "London", "accessdate": "October 24, 2012", "last": "Davies", "first": "Lizzy"}
According to Korean newspaper The Dong-a Ilbo, Psy was appointed as a goodwill ambassador of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?bicode=060000&biid=2012102572108", "title": "UN chief gets down 'Gangnam Style' with rapper Psy", "publisher": "The Dong-a Ilbo"}
On November 7, 2012, Psy held a speech in England at the Oxford Union to discuss the inspiration behind "Gangnam Style" and his next album. He told the audience that due to the success of "Gangnam Style" he is now living in both a dream and a nightmare, as it will be difficult for his next song to equal "Gangnam Style"'s success. He also talked about his early life and the moment he realized "Gangnam Style" became famous. According to The Independent, tickets for his speech were "in such demand they had to be assigned by ballot—a method not required when former presidential candidate John McCain spoke earlier that year, nor when Mother Teresa, the Dalai Lama nor Michael Jackson spoke".{"citetype": "news", "title": "Psy has the Oxford Union in raptures, Gangnam style", "url": "https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/psy-has-the-oxford-union-in-raptures-gangnam-style-8293994.html", "work": "The Independent", "location": "London", "accessdate": "November 7, 2012", "last": "Peck", "first": "Tom"}
