Following the concert, a media report revealed that Psy received death threats prior to entering the country and this was the reason for the delay in Psy's on-stage appearance. Psy eventually performed for ten minutes to an excited crowd. The media report also reported on a press conference at the Jelutong Gerakan Chinese New Year open house that revealed that questions were raised over the financing of the event. State Barisan Nasional (BN) party chief Teng Chang Yeow explained that the event "was sponsored by private sponsors who preferred to remain anonymous as they are afraid of being 'victimised' if their identities were revealed". Teng also stated that he was given the choice of a Justin Bieber visit, but chose Psy as he didn't know who Bieber was at the time.{"citetype": "news", "date": "February 14, 2013", "title": "Teng says attempt on Psy's life forced Najib to leave stage", "url": "http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/teng-says-attempt-on-psys-life-forced-najib-to-leave-stage/", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20131203005446/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/teng-says-attempt-on-psys-life-forced-najib-to-leave-stage/", "accessdate": "December 7, 2013", "newspaper": "The Malaysian Insider", "author": "Opalyn Mok"}

Questionable song title and revision of lyrics
In March 2013, South Korean media reported that the title of Psy's upcoming single would contain the word "Assarabia",{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://english.khan.co.kr/khan_art_view.html?artid=201303181825097&code=960802", "title": "Ready with a Song to Follow 'Gangnam Style'", "last": "Su-Jin", "first": "Kang", "publisher": "[[Kyunghyang Shinmun]]"} a slang used by South Koreans to express thrills, or simply to describe something satisfying. There were numerous objections to that upcoming title, and worries have risen that people of Arabic descent might misinterpret the title and find it derogatory.{"citetype": "news", "title": "PSY to revise song over worry it may offend Arabs", "url": "http://bigstory.ap.org/article/psy-revise-song-over-worry-it-may-offend-arabs", "agency": "Associated Press"}
After being questioned by a correspondent of the Voice of America about the upcoming track's potential to offend, Psy voiced out that there has been some misunderstanding and his upcoming song will undergo a major revamp.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.voanews.com/content/south-korean-artist-psy-tells-voa-via-twitter-next-single-will-not-carry-offensive-title/1623536.html", "title": "'Gangnam Style' Artist Says Title of Next Single Will Not Offend", "last": "Herman", "first": "Steve", "publisher": "[[Voice of America]]"} On March 19, 2013, he revised his song's title and lyrics over "worries it could offend Arabs".{"citetype": "news", "title": "PSY to revise song over worry it may offend Arabs", "url": "http://bigstory.ap.org/article/psy-revise-song-over-worry-it-may-offend-arabs", "agency": "Associated Press"} Many people consider the change of his song title deliberate, aimed solely at building publicity for a strong follow-up to "Gangnam Style".{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.voanews.com/content/south-korean-artist-psy-tells-voa-via-twitter-next-single-will-not-carry-offensive-title/1623536.html", "title": "'Gangnam Style' Artist Says Title of Next Single Will Not Offend", "last": "Herman", "first": "Steve", "publisher": "[[Voice of America]]"} He subsequently renamed the song "Gentleman" and released it on April 12, 2013.

Reported earnings
